there are three types of permission 
-r = read
-w = write
-x = execute

each permission can be controlled at three levels
-u = user
-g = group
-o = other

file directory can be displayed by running ls -l command
. -rwx(for user)rwx(for froup)rwx(for others)


important! = we can change the permissions with the command "chmod"

let's say we have a file named abc abd when we run ls -l abc;
-rw-r--r--. 1 calvin calvin 0 Feb 25 12:15 abc

so if we want group to not have write we need to remove write permission for group
calvin@localhost:~$ chmod g-w abc

if we want to remove read permission for everyone we run 
calvin@localhost:~$ chmod a-r abc

if we want other has the permission to read;
calvin@localhost:~$ chmod o+r abc

if there is a folder and i want everyone not to execute/enter the folder
calvin@localhost:~$ chmod a-x folder
